         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">The Camp. ¶ Sunningdale. ¶ March 4 /88 ¶ My dear Baron ¶  ¶ I thank you very heartily for your kind letter of congratulations of 4/1/88. ¶ Letter not found. ¶  ¶ The Copley Medal was an honor which I ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">88.03.04</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M3, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style=""/>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; text-align: center; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn0" n="1">
                  <p rend="FootnoteText"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>MS black-edged.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                  </p>
               </note>
               <seg rend="formtext" style="color: #2F5496; font-variant: small-caps; ">The Camp.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; text-align: center; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg rend="formtext" style="color: #2F5496; font-variant: small-caps; ">Sunningdale.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">March 4 /88</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Baron</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I thank you very heartily for your kind letter of congratulations of 4/1/88.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn1" n="2">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letter not found.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>The Copley Medal was an honor which I can truly say I never contemplated being ever nominated for;<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn2" n="3">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The Copley Medal is generally seen as the highest honour awarded by the Royal Society of London.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>and in my old age I felt that I had been rewarded enough &amp; to spare — I do hope your turn of the R. S. honors may not be delayed — I hope I need not say that your name has not escaped my recommendation<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn3" n="4">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See M to P. Sclater, December 1887.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>— but as you are aware, where all classes of Scientific men have to be considered, it is not easy to balance claims.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Thanks again for your notice of Brian.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn4" n="5">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Hooker's son.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>I am sincerely sorry to see him going in for speculations in Gold mining in Queensland. His position under the Govt. is so honorable that he should be content with it. He is he informs me engaged to be married to a Melbourne lady.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Yes, the task of a Lamarckian key is enormously difficult.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn5" n="6">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M was struggling with the preparation of B88.11.02; see Lucas, Maroske, and Brown-May (2006), pp 46–50.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>I have tried it myself — but when I have done so I have thrown affinity to the wind, finding it impossible to correlate artificial &amp; natural characters.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I cannot encourage you to hope that your attempt will meet with the recognition that its labor &amp; merit deserve — from the simple but lamentable fact that Systematic work is ignored in the present condition of Botany. The Flora of British India is ignored, &amp; I am not aware of any comments on the many reforms introduced into the Natural Orders in the Gen. Plant. The Orders<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Coniferae</hi>
               </seg>,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Coniferae</hi>
               </seg>
               <seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn6" n="7">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">word repeated.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>&amp;<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Rubiaceae</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Melastomaceae</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>&amp;c are completely remodelled as are many others. For my own part I never look for recognition or acknowledgement of such labors.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>We are still mourning A Gray's death;<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn7" n="8">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Asa Gray died on 30 January 1888.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>he &amp; Mrs Gray spent last summer in Europe, &amp; made a tour with us in Normandy, &amp; he left this house for his home at the end of September in perfect health. I had known him intimately since 1858. You will find a notice of him by now in "Nature"<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn8" n="9">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Hooker<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(1888).</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>—<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am in hopes that you may still get more New Guinea collections to describe. — they seem to come slowly in, &amp; Forbes last expedition to have been a failure.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn9" n="10">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The 'last expedition' led by Henry Forbes was 1 October to 7 November 1887, but it was undertaken for the Commissioner for British New Guinea and was purely a geographical survey. It was fraught with difficulties but never inended to collect specimens;<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>see Forbes (1888).</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am very sorry that you can give no better account of your health, &amp; do hope that it will soon be restored — there is so much work still to be done —</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>With regard to<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Nablonium</hi>
               </seg>, no doubt you are right, &amp; that Bauer's plants are all King's Island, which I had probably then regarded as appertaining to the S. Australian Flora.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn10" n="11">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The letter with M's comment has not been found.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>J.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Hooker (1855–60), vol. 1, p. 190,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>states that the distribution of<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Nablonium calyceroides</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="2"/>is<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>'South coast of Australia, Bauer'<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>[i.e. Ferdinand Bauer].<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>M's comment to Hooker probably resulted from his preparing B89.12.03, in which (p. 140) he showed this species with a Tasmanian distribution.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Ever my dear Baron</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Sincerely yr</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Jos. D. Hooker</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Coniferae</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Melastomaceae</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Nablonium</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">Rubiaceae</seg>
            </p>
         </div>
      </body>
